First, let's find the Cartesian products A x B and B x A.

A x B = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3)}
B x A = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (3, 1), (3, 2)}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference (A x B) ∆ (B x A). The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

(A x B) ∆ (B x A) = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2)} - {(2, 2)}

(A x B) ∆ (B x A) = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 3), (2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2)}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference (B x A) ∆ (A x B).

(B x A) ∆ (A x B) = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (3, 1), (3, 2), (1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3)} - {(2, 2)}

(B x A) ∆ (A x B) = {(2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2), (1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 3)}

As we can see, (A x B) ∆ (B x A) = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 3), (2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2)} and (B x A) ∆ (A x B) = {(2, 1), (3, 1), (3, 2), (1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 3)}. These two sets are equal, so the statement "Show that (A x B) ∆ (B x A) is not equal to (B x A) ∆ (A x B)" is incorrect. In fact, (A x B) ∆ (B x A) is equal to (B x A) ∆ (A x B).
